HPC with Slurm - Physical Server Setup
1 Master Node + 3 Worker Nodes
=======================================
Plain language. No fluff. Just what you need.


ASSUMPTIONS
-----------
  - All 4 servers are running Ubuntu 22.04 LTS
  - All servers are on the same local network
  - You have root access on all machines
  - Static IPs are already assigned

Our setup:
  master  192.168.1.10
  worker1 192.168.1.11
  worker2 192.168.1.12
  worker3 192.168.1.13

This guide assumes root SSH access is enabled.

On every node:

Set a root password:

    sudo passwd root

Edit SSH configuration:

    sudo nano /etc/ssh/sshd_config

Find:

    #PermitRootLogin prohibit-password

Change to:

    PermitRootLogin yes

Ensure:

    PasswordAuthentication yes

Restart SSH:

    sudo systemctl restart ssh

Test from another node:

    ssh root@worker1


================================================================
PART 1 - SETTING UP THE MASTER NODE
================================================================
Run everything as root.

First, set the hostname on the master:

    hostnamectl set-hostname master

Reboot or log out/in after changing the hostname to ensure all services pick up the new hostname.

Edit /etc/hosts on ALL machines (master and all workers).
Add these lines at the bottom:

    192.168.1.10  master
    192.168.1.11  worker1
    192.168.1.12  worker2
    192.168.1.13  worker3

This lets all machines talk to each other by name.

-- Install required packages on master --

    apt update && apt upgrade -y
    apt install -y munge slurm-wlm nfs-kernel-server slurmctld slurmdbd

-- Set up Munge on master --

Munge handles authentication between all nodes.
Generate the munge key (only do this on master):

    For Ubuntu 24.04, the munge key is automatically generated during package installation.

    Verify it exists:

        ls -l /etc/munge/munge.key

    If the key is missing, generate one manually:

        mungekey
        chown munge:munge /etc/munge/munge.key
        chmod 400 /etc/munge/munge.key

Start and enable munge:

    systemctl enable munge
    systemctl start munge

Test it:
    munge -n | unmunge

You should see "STATUS: Success". If not, check ownership of munge.key.

-- Set up NFS shared storage on master --

All nodes need to share the same home directory so job scripts and
output files are visible everywhere.

Create the shared directory:

    mkdir -p /shared
    chown nobody:nogroup /shared
    chmod 777 /shared

Edit /etc/exports and add:
Replace 192.168.1.0/24 with the subnet used by your cluster network.
    For example:
        192.168.0.0/24
        10.0.0.0/24

    /shared  192.168.1.0/24(rw,sync,no_subtree_check,no_root_squash)

Apply the export:

    exportfs -a
    systemctl enable nfs-kernel-server
    systemctl start nfs-kernel-server

-- Create slurm user on master --

Slurm needs a dedicated system user. Same UID/GID must exist on ALL nodes.

If the slurm user does not already exist:

    groupadd -g 1001 slurm
    useradd -m -c "Slurm Workload Manager" -d /var/lib/slurm \
            -u 1001 -g slurm -s /bin/bash slurm

Otherwise, keep the existing slurm user and ensure the same UID/GID exists on all nodes.

-- Create Slurm directories on master --

    mkdir -p /var/spool/slurmctld
    mkdir -p /var/log/slurm
    chown slurm:slurm /var/spool/slurmctld
    chown slurm:slurm /var/log/slurm

-- Optional: Configure Slurm Accounting (sacct support) --

If you want to track completed jobs using:
    sacct

or manage users, accounts, and cluster statistics, configure SlurmDBD before creating `slurm.conf`.

Install MariaDB:
    apt install -y mariadb-server

Enable and start:
    systemctl enable mariadb
    systemctl start mariadb

Secure the installation:    
    mysql_secure_installation

Create the accounting database:
    mysql -u root -p

Inside MariaDB:
    CREATE DATABASE slurm_acct_db;

    CREATE USER 'slurm'@'localhost'
    IDENTIFIED BY 'StrongPasswordHere';

    GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES
    ON slurm_acct_db.*
    TO 'slurm'@'localhost';

    FLUSH PRIVILEGES;

    EXIT;

Create:
    /etc/slurm/slurmdbd.conf

with:
    AuthType=auth/munge

    DbdHost=master
    DbdPort=6819

    SlurmUser=slurm

    StorageType=accounting_storage/mysql

    StorageHost=localhost
    StoragePort=3306

    StorageUser=slurm
    StoragePass=StrongPasswordHere

    StorageLoc=slurm_acct_db

Secure the file:
    chown slurm:slurm /etc/slurm/slurmdbd.conf
    chmod 600 /etc/slurm/slurmdbd.conf

Enable and start SlurmDBD:
    systemctl enable slurmdbd
    systemctl start slurmdbd

Verify:
    systemctl status slurmdbd

The following settings must then be added to `slurm.conf`:
    AccountingStorageType=accounting_storage/slurmdbd
    AccountingStorageHost=master
    AccountingStoragePort=6819

    JobAcctGatherType=jobacct_gather/linux

After Slurm is configured and running:
    sacctmgr add cluster mycluster

Verify:
    sacctmgr show cluster

Accounting can be tested with:
    sacct

This section is optional. If omitted, Slurm scheduling and job execution still work normally, but completed-job history and accounting features will not be available.


-- Write the slurm.conf on master --

This is the main Slurm configuration file.

Before creating the configuration, gather hardware information from each worker:

    slurmd -C

Use the reported CPUs and RealMemory values when defining nodes.

Create /etc/slurm/slurm.conf:

    ClusterName=mycluster

    SlurmctldHost=master

    AuthType=auth/munge

    SlurmUser=slurm

    StateSaveLocation=/var/spool/slurmctld
    SlurmdSpoolDir=/var/spool/slurmd

    SlurmctldPidFile=/run/slurmctld.pid
    SlurmdPidFile=/run/slurmd.pid

    SlurmctldPort=6817
    SlurmdPort=6818

    SwitchType=switch/none
    MpiDefault=none

    ProctrackType=proctrack/linuxproc
    ReturnToService=2

    TaskPlugin=task/affinity

    # Logging
    SlurmctldLogFile=/var/log/slurm/slurmctld.log
    SlurmdLogFile=/var/log/slurm/slurmd.log

    # Scheduling
    SchedulerType=sched/backfill
    SelectType=select/cons_tres
    SelectTypeParameters=CR_Core

    # Accounting (optional but recommended)
    AccountingStorageType=accounting_storage/slurmdbd
    AccountingStorageHost=master
    AccountingStoragePort=6819

    JobAcctGatherType=jobacct_gather/linux

    # Time limits and cleanup
    InactiveLimit=0
    KillWait=30
    MinJobAge=300

    SlurmctldTimeout=120
    SlurmdTimeout=300

    # Node definitions
    # Adjust CPUs and RealMemory to match your actual hardware
    NodeName=worker1 NodeAddr=192.168.1.11 CPUs=8 RealMemory=16000 State=UNKNOWN
    NodeName=worker2 NodeAddr=192.168.1.12 CPUs=8 RealMemory=16000 State=UNKNOWN
    NodeName=worker3 NodeAddr=192.168.1.13 CPUs=8 RealMemory=16000 State=UNKNOWN

    # Partition (queue) definition
    PartitionName=normal Nodes=worker[1-3] Default=YES MaxTime=INFINITE State=UP


Notes:

* Replace master with your controller hostname.
* Replace all IP addresses with your actual node IPs.
* Replace CPUs and RealMemory with values reported by `slurmd -C`.
* If a worker's Linux hostname differs from its Slurm node name, add:
    NodeHostname=<actual-linux-hostname>

  Example:
    NodeName=worker1 NodeHostname=my-laptop NodeAddr=192.168.1.11 CPUs=8 RealMemory=16000 State=UNKNOWN

-- Start slurmctld on master --

    systemctl enable slurmctld
    systemctl start slurmctld

Check it's running:
    systemctl status slurmctld

Check the log if something went wrong:
    tail -f /var/log/slurm/slurmctld.log


================================================================
PART 2 - SETTING UP EACH WORKER NODE
================================================================

Do these steps on worker1, worker2, and worker3.
Run everything as root.

-- Set hostname (do on each worker separately) --

On worker1:   hostnamectl set-hostname worker1
On worker2:   hostnamectl set-hostname worker2
On worker3:   hostnamectl set-hostname worker3

-- Edit /etc/hosts on each worker --

Same as master. Add all four entries:

    192.168.1.10  master
    192.168.1.11  worker1
    192.168.1.12  worker2
    192.168.1.13  worker3

-- Install packages on each worker --

    apt update && apt upgrade -y
    apt install -y munge slurm-wlm slurmd nfs-common

-- Copy munge key from master to each worker --

Back on the MASTER, copy the key to each worker:

    scp /etc/munge/munge.key root@worker1:/etc/munge/munge.key
    scp /etc/munge/munge.key root@worker2:/etc/munge/munge.key
    scp /etc/munge/munge.key root@worker3:/etc/munge/munge.key

Now on EACH WORKER, fix permissions:

    chown munge:munge /etc/munge/munge.key
    chmod 400 /etc/munge/munge.key
    systemctl enable munge
    systemctl start munge

Test munge on each worker:
    munge -n | unmunge

Should say "STATUS: Success".

-- Mount shared NFS on each worker --

    mkdir -p /shared

Edit /etc/fstab on each worker and add this line:

    master:/shared  /shared  nfs  defaults  0  0

Mount it now without rebooting:

    mount -a

If you see a warning that systemd is using an older version of the file, reload systemd and try again:

    systemctl daemon-reload
    mount -a

Check it mounted:
    df -h | grep shared

-- Create slurm user on each worker --

The slurm user and group must exist on every node and use the same UID/GID.

Check whether the account already exists:

    id slurm

If it does not exist, create it:

    groupadd -g 1001 slurm
    useradd -m -c "Slurm Workload Manager" -d /var/lib/slurm \
            -u 1001 -g slurm -s /bin/bash slurm

Verify the UID/GID matches the master node:

    id slurm

-- Create slurm directories on each worker --

    mkdir -p /var/spool/slurmd
    mkdir -p /var/log/slurm
    chown slurm:slurm /var/spool/slurmd
    chown slurm:slurm /var/log/slurm

-- Copy slurm.conf from master to each worker --

On MASTER, run:

    scp /etc/slurm/slurm.conf root@worker1:/etc/slurm/slurm.conf
    scp /etc/slurm/slurm.conf root@worker2:/etc/slurm/slurm.conf
    scp /etc/slurm/slurm.conf root@worker3:/etc/slurm/slurm.conf

Every node must have the identical slurm.conf. If you change it on master
later, copy it out to workers again.

-- Start slurmd on each worker --

    systemctl enable slurmd
    systemctl start slurmd

Check status:
    systemctl status slurmd

Check log:
    tail -f /var/log/slurm/slurmd.log


================================================================
PART 3 - SETTING UP COMMUNICATION BETWEEN MASTER AND WORKERS
================================================================

Slurm uses Munge for authentication (already done above), but there are
a few more things to make communication smooth.

-- Set up SSH key-based login from master to all workers --

On MASTER only:

    ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096 -N "" -f /root/.ssh/id_rsa

Copy the public key to each worker:

    ssh-copy-id root@worker1
    ssh-copy-id root@worker2
    ssh-copy-id root@worker3

Test it:
    ssh root@worker1 hostname
    ssh root@worker2 hostname
    ssh root@worker3 hostname

Each should return the worker hostname without asking for a password.

-- Open firewall ports (do on ALL nodes) --

Slurm uses ports 6817 (slurmctld) and 6818 (slurmd).

    ufw allow 6817/tcp
    ufw allow 6818/tcp
    ufw allow from 192.168.1.0/24

NFS needs these:

    ufw allow from 192.168.1.0/24 to any port 2049

-- Verify nodes are visible from master --

On MASTER:

    sinfo

You should see all three workers listed. State will be "idle" if everything
is working. If state is "down" or "unk", check:

  1. Is slurmd running on that worker?
  2. Is munge running on that worker?
  3. Can master SSH into that worker?
  4. Is the slurm.conf identical on all nodes?

To bring a node back up manually:

    scontrol update nodename=worker1 state=resume

-- Test that a job actually runs across nodes --

    srun --nodes=3 --ntasks=3 hostname

You should see worker1, worker2, worker3 each print their name.
That confirms all three are reachable and accepting work.


================================================================
PART 4 - BASIC MONITORING WITH GANGLIA
================================================================

Ganglia gives you a web dashboard showing CPU, memory, network, and disk
usage across all your nodes in real time.

Architecture:
  - gmond runs on every node (collects metrics)
  - gmetad runs on master only (aggregates metrics)
  - ganglia-web runs on master only (web UI)

-- Install on master --

    apt install -y ganglia-monitor gmetad ganglia-webfrontend apache2

-- Install gmond on each worker --

    apt install -y ganglia-monitor

-- Configure gmond on master --

Edit /etc/ganglia/gmond.conf

Find the cluster block and set:

    cluster {
      name = "mycluster"
      owner = "admin"
    }

Find the udp_send_channel block and set:

    udp_send_channel {
      host = master
      port = 8649
      ttl = 1
    }

Find the udp_recv_channel block and set:

    udp_recv_channel {
      port = 8649
    }

-- Configure gmond on each worker --

Edit /etc/ganglia/gmond.conf on each worker.

Change it so workers SEND data to master but do NOT receive:

    cluster {
      name = "mycluster"
    }

    udp_send_channel {
      host = master
      port = 8649
      ttl = 1
    }

    # Remove or comment out udp_recv_channel on workers

-- Configure gmetad on master --

Edit /etc/ganglia/gmetad.conf on master:

    data_source "mycluster" master:8649

This tells gmetad to collect from gmond running on master
(which already receives data from workers).

-- Set up Ganglia web on master --

    cp /etc/ganglia-webfrontend/apache.conf /etc/apache2/sites-enabled/ganglia.conf
    systemctl restart apache2

-- Start everything --

On master:

    systemctl enable ganglia-monitor gmetad
    systemctl start ganglia-monitor gmetad

On each worker:

    systemctl enable ganglia-monitor
    systemctl start ganglia-monitor

-- Open port for Ganglia --

    ufw allow 8649/udp
    ufw allow 80/tcp

-- Access the web UI --

Open a browser and go to:

    http://192.168.1.10/ganglia

You should see all four nodes listed with live CPU and memory graphs.
It may take 1-2 minutes for data to start showing up after first launch.

-- Firewall for Ganglia (on all nodes) --

    ufw allow 8649/udp

-- Troubleshooting --

Check gmond:

systemctl status ganglia-monitor

Check gmetad:

systemctl status gmetad

Check Apache:

systemctl status apache2

Check Ganglia data:

gstat -a

Check Apache errors:

tail -f /var/log/apache2/error.log

NOTE (Ubuntu 24.04):

Ganglia Web Frontend 3.7.x may show HTTP 500 errors due to PHP compatibility issues.

If that happens, inspect:

tail -f /var/log/apache2/error.log

and install a compatible PHP version if required.

================================================================
PART 5 - SUBMITTING JOBS AND MONITORING THE JOB QUEUE
================================================================

All job submission is done from the MASTER node.

-- Basic job submission --

Quickest way, no script needed:

    sbatch --wrap="hostname && sleep 10"

With a job script (recommended for real work):

Create /shared/job.sh:

    #!/bin/bash
    #SBATCH --job-name=test-job
    #SBATCH --nodes=2
    #SBATCH --ntasks=4
    #SBATCH --cpus-per-task=1
    #SBATCH --mem=2G
    #SBATCH --time=00:05:00
    #SBATCH --output=/shared/output-%j.txt
    #SBATCH --error=/shared/error-%j.txt

    echo "Job ID: $SLURM_JOB_ID"
    echo "Running on: $SLURM_NODELIST"
    echo "Start time: $(date)"
    srun hostname
    sleep 30
    echo "Done: $(date)"

Submit it:

    sbatch /shared/job.sh

-- Monitoring the job queue --

See all jobs currently queued or running:
    squeue

See jobs for a specific user:
    squeue -u youruser

See jobs with more detail:
    squeue -l

Watch the queue update every 3 seconds:
    watch -n 3 squeue

See full details of a specific job:
    scontrol show job <jobid>

-- Understanding job states --

    PD  = Pending (waiting for resources)
    R   = Running
    CG  = Completing (cleaning up)
    CD  = Completed
    F   = Failed
    CA  = Cancelled

If a job is stuck in PD, check why:
    squeue --reason

Common reasons: Resources (not enough free), Priority, Dependency

-- Check node status while jobs run --

    sinfo
    sinfo -N -l         (detailed per-node view)

-- Job history and accounting --

See jobs that have already finished:

    sacct

See specific job details:
    sacct -j <jobid> --format=JobID,JobName,State,Elapsed,CPUTime,MaxRSS

-- Submit an array job --

Good for running the same task many times with different inputs:

    sbatch --array=1-10 /shared/job.sh

Each task gets a unique $SLURM_ARRAY_TASK_ID variable you can use
to differentiate inputs.

-- Cancel a job --

    scancel <jobid>

Cancel all your jobs:
    scancel -u youruser

Cancel all pending jobs only:
    scancel -t PD -u youruser


================================================================
PART 6 - LIVE RESOURCE UTILIZATION VIA WEB
================================================================

You already have Ganglia from Part 4 which gives CPU/memory/network graphs.
Here are a couple more options depending on what level of detail you need.

-- Option A: Ganglia (already set up) --

URL: http://192.168.1.10/ganglia

What it shows:
  - Per-node CPU usage (live graph)
  - Memory used/free
  - Network in/out
  - Disk I/O
  - Load average
  - You can click on individual nodes for their own graphs

Best for: quick hardware health view, historical graphs

-- Option B: Slurm-web (Slurm-specific dashboard) --

This shows Slurm job queue and node allocation in a browser.

Install on master:

    apt install -y python3-pip
    pip3 install slurm-web

Or use the community version:

    git clone https://github.com/edf-hpc/slurm-web
    cd slurm-web
    pip3 install -r requirements.txt

Configure it to point at your Slurm REST API or slurmctld socket,
then run it. Check the project's README for the exact startup command
as it varies by version.

URL once running: http://192.168.1.10:5000

What it shows:
  - Job queue in real time
  - Which nodes are running what jobs
  - Node state (idle, allocated, drained)

-- Option C: Grafana + Prometheus + DCGM (advanced) --

If you want a really polished real-time dashboard this is the standard
modern approach. More setup involved but much more powerful.

Steps at a high level:

  1. Install Prometheus on master
     apt install prometheus

  2. Install node_exporter on ALL nodes
     apt install prometheus-node-exporter
     This collects CPU, memory, disk, network metrics automatically

  3. Configure Prometheus to scrape all nodes
     Edit /etc/prometheus/prometheus.yml and add:

         scrape_configs:
           - job_name: 'nodes'
             static_configs:
               - targets:
                 - master:9100
                 - worker1:9100
                 - worker2:9100
                 - worker3:9100

     Restart: systemctl restart prometheus

  4. Install Grafana on master

         apt install -y software-properties-common
         add-apt-repository "deb https://packages.grafana.com/oss/deb stable main"
         apt update && apt install grafana
         systemctl enable grafana-server
         systemctl start grafana-server

  5. Open Grafana at http://192.168.1.10:3000
     Default login: admin / admin

  6. Add Prometheus as a data source in Grafana UI
     Settings > Data Sources > Add > Prometheus
     URL: http://localhost:9090

  7. Import the Node Exporter Full dashboard
     Go to Dashboards > Import
     Enter dashboard ID: 1860
     Select your Prometheus source
     Click Import

You now have a live dashboard showing all 4 nodes with CPU, memory,
disk IO, network, and load average updating every few seconds.

-- Ports to open for these services --

    ufw allow 3000/tcp    # Grafana
    ufw allow 9090/tcp    # Prometheus
    ufw allow 9100/tcp    # node_exporter (from master only ideally)
    ufw allow 5000/tcp    # slurm-web if you use it

-- Recommended combination for a demo --

  Use Ganglia for hardware-level metrics (it's already set up).
  Use "watch -n 2 squeue" in a terminal for the job queue.
  Use Grafana + Prometheus if you want a really impressive live dashboard.

That gives you everything visible without much extra work.


